# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1914-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1914-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-world-series/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1914-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:1914-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:1914-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1914-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:1914-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:1914-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:1914-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1914-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:1914-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:1914-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:1914-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1914-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1914-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1914-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1914-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1914-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1875 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their fourth consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 71–8 to win the pennant by 15 games.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 62 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 54 wins.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Deacon White (.367), second baseman Ross Barnes (.364), and first baseman Cal McVey (.355) finished 1–2–3 in the league's batting race.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] McVey paced the circuit with 87 runs batted in, and outfielder Jim O'Rourke had the most home runs, with 6.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Boston offense scored more runs than any other team in the NA.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] This was the last season of the Association, which dissolved at the end of the year.
[src:1914-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings club would join the new National League in 1876.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The **1914 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's 1914 season.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The 11th edition of the World Series, it was played between the American League (AL) champion and defending World Series champion Philadelphia Athletics and the National League (NL) champion Boston Braves.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The "Miracle Braves" were in last place on July 4, then won the National League pennant by 10+1⁄2 games.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The Braves' relatively unknown starting trio of pitchers, with a combined career record of 285–245, outperformed the Athletics' vaunted rotation (929–654) in all four games.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Hank Gowdy hit .545 (6 of 11) with five extra-base hits and also drew five walks for Boston in the series and made the difference in Games 1 and 3.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Adding to their supposed disadvantages, the Braves arguably lacked a notable home-field advantage.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] They had abandoned their 43-year-old home field South End Grounds in August 1914, choosing to rent from the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park while awaiting construction of Braves Field (1915).
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Thus their home games in this Series were also at Fenway.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] This was the first official four-game sweep in World Series history.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The Chicago Cubs had defeated the Detroit Tigers four games to none in 1907, but Game 1 had ended in a tie before the Cubs won the next four in a row.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Cohan through bookmaker Sport Sullivan, who was also implicated in the 1919 Black Sox scandal.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Chief Bender and Eddie Plank jumped to the rival Federal League for the 1915 season.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Mack unloaded most of his other high-priced stars soon after and, within two years, the A's posted the worst winning percentage in modern history (even worse than the 1962 New York Mets and the 2024 Chicago White Sox).
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Because an AL team had won the last four World Series (the A's had represented the AL in three out of those four), the A's were heavily favored.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The fact that the Braves had been in last place in July before coming back to win the pennant contributed to the perception that the AL was simply superior to the NL.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The A's roster boasted five future Hall of Famers and many agreed they were the better team on paper.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] A story told about Connie Mack during the 1914 season reflects this attitude among the A's that the Braves would be pushovers.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] That year, Mack gave star pitcher Chief Bender the week off and told him to scout the Braves personally.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] After having won 26 games, Dick Rudolph scattered five hits while striking out eight as the Braves won the opener in convincing fashion against the Athletics' ace, Chief Bender.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Catcher Hank Gowdy had a single, double and triple as well as a walk in leading Boston's offensive attack.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] He was also on the back end of a double steal in the eighth inning, with Butch Schmidt's steal of home the Braves' final run.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] In Tom Meany's 1950 book *Baseball's Greatest Teams*, with one chapter discussing what the author thought each of the then 16 major league teams' single most outstanding season was, the chapter on the Boston Braves was naturally on their one world championship year, 1914.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Meany may also have been the source for the sensational sidelight that Stallings' motive for this may have been the rumor that the A's may have sabotaged the Shibe Park visiting clubhouse (with war clouds gathering in Europe as World War I was just beginning).
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Bill James, Boston's other 26-game winner, hooked up against Philadelphia's Eddie Plank in a classic pitcher's duel.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] James allowed only three base runners in the first eight innings, picking off two of them in holding Philadelphia scoreless.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Plank matched him until the ninth, when Amos Strunk lost Charlie Deal's fly ball in the sun for a double.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Deal then stole third, and scored on a two-out single by Les Mann.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] James walked two batters in the ninth, but got Eddie Murphy to ground into a game-ending double play to give Boston a 2–0 advantage in the series coming back home to Fenway.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Lefty Tyler of the Braves went up against Bullet Joe Bush in a 12-inning thriller.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Frank "Home Run" Baker's two-out single in the tenth plated two runs to give the Athletics a 4–2 lead and a seeming victory to get them back in the series.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] But Hank Gowdy led off the bottom of the tenth with a home run, and the Braves then tied the game on Joe Connolly's sacrifice fly later in the inning.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Game 2 winner Bill James, coming on in relief for Boston in the 11th, earned the win after Gowdy led off the bottom of the 12th with a double and pinch-runner Les Mann scored when Bush threw wildly to third on Herbie Moran's bunt, giving the Braves a commanding 3–0 series lead.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Johnny Evers' two-out, two-run single in the bottom of the fifth broke a 1–1 tie and the collective backs of the heavily favored Athletics as the "Miracle Braves" completed their improbable sweep.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] Game 1 winner Dick Rudolph allowed only one base-runner after Evers' tie-breaking hit and struck out seven in notching his second win of the series.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The powerful A's were held to a .172 team batting average and no home runs in the series.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] This was the only championship the Braves won during their time in Boston, as the team would move to Milwaukee, Wisconsin in 1953.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] They would make one more World Series appearance before the move in 1948, which they lost to the Cleveland Indians in six games.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The Braves would win their next championship in 1957 over the New York Yankees in seven games, which would be the only championship they won in Milwaukee, as the team then moved to Atlanta in 1966.
[src:1914-world-series/1914-world-series] The Athletics would return to the World Series in 1929, and defeated the Chicago Cubs in five games.
